Health and safety:
Require most businesses to pay a [new employer Medicare contribution](https://elizabethwarren.com/plans/paying-for-m4a) that
• initially sets an employer's contribution to 98 percent of the amount they pay on health care spending (calculated by multiplying the average cost per employee in the prior three years, adjusted for increases in national health care spending, by the number of people the business employs);   
• applies special rules for self-employed individuals, small businesses, and new and expanding companies;
• reduces the contributions of employers offering health benefits under collective bargaining agreements by increasing their employees' compensation by the amount the company otherwise would pay the government, but requires those companies to pay the government at least the national average cost of health care per employee;
• over time, sets employers' contributions equal to the average health care cost per employee nationally; and
• requires a supplemental employer medicare contribution  from large employers with very high executive compensation and stock buyout rates if total revenues from Warren's plan falls short of its $8.8 trillion 10-year target

